## 8. Requirement Specification

### 8.1 Functional Requirements

| Requirement | Description |
|---|---|
| Image Selection | Select image files (PNG, JPG, JPEG, BMP, GIF, TIFF, WEBP) with validation |
| Image Encryption | Encrypt images using AES-256-CBC with random IV and PKCS7 padding |
| Image Decryption | Decrypt `.enc` files back to original images with lossless quality |
| Key Generation | Generate cryptographically strong 256-bit keys (URL-safe Base64) |
| Key Derivation | Derive AES-256 keys from passwords using SHA-256 |
| Email Sending | Send encrypted files via SMTP SSL with rich HTML email body |
| Email Receiving | Download `.enc` attachments from email inbox via IMAP |
| Email Configuration | Save and load email settings from [.env](file:///c:/Users/madhu/OneDrive/%E3%83%89%E3%82%AD%E3%83%A5%E3%83%A1%E3%83%B3%E3%83%88/Desktop/imageviv/.env) file |
| Progress Tracking | Display encryption/decryption progress with status bar |
| Error Handling | Handle invalid files, wrong keys, email errors gracefully |
| Clipboard Support | Copy generated keys to clipboard |
| Password Visibility | Toggle password field visibility |

### 8.2 Software Requirements

| Software | Version / Details |
|---|---|
| Python | 3.8 or higher |
| pycryptodome | Latest (AES encryption library) |
| Pillow (PIL) | Latest (Image validation library) |
| NumPy | Latest (Numerical operations) |
| Tkinter | Built-in with Python (GUI framework) |
| smtplib | Built-in with Python (SMTP email) |
| imaplib | Built-in with Python (IMAP email) |
| hashlib | Built-in with Python (SHA-256 hashing) |
| pip | Package manager for installing dependencies |

### 8.3 Operating Systems Supported

| Operating System | Support Level |
|---|---|
| Windows 10/11 | Fully Supported (Primary) |
| macOS | Fully Supported |
| Linux (Ubuntu, Fedora, etc.) | Fully Supported |

The application is cross-platform as it uses Python with Tkinter, which is available on all major operating systems.

### 8.4 Technologies and Languages Used

| Technology | Purpose |
|---|---|
| Python 3 | Primary programming language |
| AES-256 (pycryptodome) | Image encryption and decryption |
| SHA-256 (hashlib) | Password-to-key derivation |
| Tkinter + ttk | Graphical User Interface |
| SMTP over SSL (smtplib) | Secure email sending |
| IMAP over SSL (imaplib) | Secure email receiving |
| Pillow (PIL) | Image file validation |
| .env configuration | Persistent email settings |

### 8.5 Hardware Requirements

| Component | Minimum Requirement |
|---|---|
| Processor | Dual-core CPU (Intel i3 or equivalent) |
| RAM | 4 GB minimum (8 GB recommended) |
| Disk Space | 500 MB (for Python, libraries, and image processing) |
| Network | Internet connection required for email functionality |
| Display | 1024 × 768 minimum resolution |
| Input | Keyboard and Mouse |

---

## 9. System Testing

### 9.1 Types of Testing

#### 9.1.1 Unit Testing

Individual modules were tested independently:
- **encryptor.py**: Tested encryption and decryption of various image formats (PNG, JPG, BMP, GIF, TIFF) with different key lengths. Verified PKCS7 padding/unpadding logic with edge cases.
- **key_manager.py**: Tested key generation for randomness and format correctness. Verified SHA-256 hashing produces consistent, deterministic 32-byte outputs.
- **email_sender.py**: Tested email body construction (both plain text and HTML) with various filenames and file sizes.
- **env_config.py**: Tested [.env](file:///c:/Users/madhu/OneDrive/%E3%83%89%E3%82%AD%E3%83%A5%E3%83%A1%E3%83%B3%E3%83%88/Desktop/imageviv/.env) file parsing with comments, quoted values, special characters, and edge cases.
- **utils.py**: Tested image validation with valid images, corrupted files, and non-image files.

#### 9.1.2 Integration Testing

Modules were tested together to verify seamless interaction:
- Encryption → Email Sending pipeline
- Email Receiving → Decryption pipeline
- GUI → Encryption/Decryption → Status updates pipeline
- Key generation → Key hashing → Encryption → Decryption consistency

#### 9.1.3 Functional Testing

Each feature was tested for correct behavior:
- Image selection and validation
- Encryption produces valid `.enc` files
- Decryption with correct key restores the original image
- Decryption with wrong key produces an appropriate error message
- Email sending successfully transmits the encrypted file
- Email receiving correctly downloads `.enc` attachments

#### 9.1.4 System Testing

The complete application was tested end-to-end:
- Full workflow: Select image → Generate key → Encrypt → Configure email → Send → Receive → Decrypt
- Tested with various image sizes (small thumbnails to large high-resolution images)
- Tested with different image formats
- Tested under different network conditions

#### 9.1.5 White Box Testing

Internal code paths were thoroughly examined:
- All branches in encryption/decryption logic (valid data, corrupted data, empty data)
- PKCS7 padding edge cases (data exactly divisible by block size)
- MIME filename decoding with various encodings
- [.env](file:///c:/Users/madhu/OneDrive/%E3%83%89%E3%82%AD%E3%83%A5%E3%83%A1%E3%83%B3%E3%83%88/Desktop/imageviv/.env) file parsing with malformed inputs
- Error handling paths in all modules

#### 9.1.6 Black Box Testing

The system was tested from the user's perspective without knowledge of internal implementation:
- Users attempted to encrypt/decrypt images using only the GUI
- Various invalid inputs were provided (non-image files, empty keys, invalid email addresses)
- The system's response to each input was verified against expected behavior

### 9.2 Test Strategy and Approach

#### 9.2.1 Test Objectives

- Verify that AES-256 encryption correctly transforms image data into unreadable ciphertext
- Verify that decryption with the correct key produces a bit-identical copy of the original image
- Verify that decryption with an incorrect key fails gracefully with an informative error message
- Verify that email sending and receiving work correctly with various email providers
- Verify that the GUI remains responsive during heavy operations (threading)
- Verify that all error conditions are handled gracefully with user-friendly messages

#### 9.2.2 Features to be Tested

- Image file selection and validation
- AES-256-CBC encryption and decryption
- PKCS7 padding and unpadding
- SHA-256 key derivation
- Cryptographically random key generation
- Email configuration save and load
- SMTP email sending with attachment
- IMAP email receiving and attachment download
- GUI responsiveness and thread safety
- Progress bar and status updates
- Clipboard operations
- Password visibility toggle
- Error handling for all failure scenarios

### 9.3 Integration Testing

#### 9.3.1 Test Results

| Test Case | Input | Expected Output | Actual Output | Status |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Encrypt PNG image | photo.png + key | photo.png.enc created | photo.png.enc created | ✅ PASS |
| Encrypt JPG image | image.jpg + key | image.jpg.enc created | image.jpg.enc created | ✅ PASS |
| Decrypt with correct key | photo.png.enc + correct key | Original photo.png restored | Original photo.png restored | ✅ PASS |
| Decrypt with wrong key | photo.png.enc + wrong key | Error message displayed | "Decryption failed" error shown | ✅ PASS |
| Lossless verification | Original vs Decrypted | Files are byte-identical | Files are byte-identical | ✅ PASS |
| Send encrypted file | .enc file + email config | Email sent successfully | Email sent successfully | ✅ PASS |
| Receive .enc attachment | Check inbox | .enc file downloaded | .enc file downloaded to downloads/ | ✅ PASS |
| Generate strong key | Click Generate | 44-char Base64 key | 44-char Base64 key generated | ✅ PASS |
| Invalid image selection | text.txt selected | Error: Not a valid image | "Invalid Image" error shown | ✅ PASS |
| Empty key encryption | Image selected, no key | Error: Missing key | "Missing Key" error shown | ✅ PASS |

